    description: `Waqiyah Maeraj Aur uus Kai Mushahidaat is a detailed Urdu-language account of the miraculous Night Journey and Ascension (Al-Isra wal-Mi'raj) of the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). Published under the History category, this book provides a comprehensive narration of one of the most extraordinary events in the life of the Prophet and in all of human religious history. The title translates to "The Event of the Ascension and Its Observations," indicating the book's focus on what the Prophet (peace be upon him) witnessed during this miraculous journey through the heavens.

The book begins by establishing the historical context of the event, including the year in which the Mi'raj occurred, the circumstances of the Prophet's life at that time — including the recent loss of his beloved wife Khadijah (may Allah be pleased with her) and his uncle Abu Talib, a period known as the Year of Sorrow — and the significance of this miracle in the broader narrative of prophetic history. The author then provides a detailed account of the first part of the journey, Al-Isra, in which the Prophet was transported from Makkah to Jerusalem (Al-Aqsa Mosque) on the miraculous beast called Al-Buraq.

The core of the book is devoted to the Ascension (Mi'raj) itself, where the Prophet (peace be upon him) was taken through the seven heavens. The author describes each heavenly encounter in detail, including the Prophet's meetings with previous prophets such as Adam, Isa (Jesus), Yusuf (Joseph), Idris (Enoch), Harun (Aaron), Musa (Moses), and Ibrahim (Abraham), peace be upon them all. The narrative includes the conversations that took place during these meetings, the greetings exchanged, and the significance of each prophet's placement in the respective heaven.

The book gives particular attention to the most significant moments of the journey, including the Prophet's being brought before the divine presence, the gift of the five daily prayers, the negotiations with Musa (peace be upon him) regarding the number of prayers, and the vision of Paradise and Hell. The author carefully distinguishes between narrations that are authentically reported and those of lesser reliability, maintaining scholarly rigor throughout.

The concluding sections discuss the impact of the Mi'raj on the early Muslim community, the reaction of the Quraysh when the Prophet reported the event, Abu Bakr's famous response that earned him the title As-Siddiq (the truthful), and the enduring lessons that Muslims can draw from this miraculous event. The book is written in clear Urdu prose that brings the narrative to life while maintaining its scholarly and religious significance.`,
